    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Free Trade: Why Labor Is Wary</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Gary Chaison objects to suggstions that labor law reform be linked to free trade (May 9 Op-Ed)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman (column,  May 9) argues that a good way to reduce the unions' resistance to free trade is by having the government empower them and enable them to thrive in the new, open economy.  This can be done, he believes, by reducing management's capacity to permanently replace striking workers and by increasing penalties on employers who interfere with their workers' right to unionize.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman (column,  May 9) argues that a good way to reduce the unions' resistance to free trade is by having the government empower them and enable them to thrive in the new, open economy.  This can be done, he believes, by reducing management's capacity to permanently replace striking workers and by increasing penalties on employers who interfere with their workers' right to unionize.</p>
        <p>Why does labor law reform have to be linked to free trade? Even without the threat of expanding trade, workers would deserve broadly defined and strongly enforced rights to join unions and engage in collective bargaining.</p>
        <p>GARY  CHAISON  Worcester, Mass., May 9, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of industrial relations at Clark University.</p>
      </block>
